# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: android-runtime-art
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] In computer science, **ahead-of-time compilation** (**AOT compilation**) is the act of compiling an (often) higher-level programming language into an (often) lower-level language before execution of a program, usually at build-time, to reduce the amount of work needed to be performed at run time.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] When being used in this context, it is often seen as an opposite of just-in-time (JIT) compiling.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] Speaking more generally, the target languages of an AOT compilation are not necessarily specific to native machine code but are defined rather arbitrarily.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] Some academic papers use this word to mean the act of compiling the Java bytecode to C or the timing when optimization pipeline are performed.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] An academic project uses this word to mean the act of pre-compiling JavaScript to a machine-dependent optimized IR for V8 (JavaScript engine) and to a machine independent bytecode for JavaScriptCore.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] Some industrial language implementations (e.g.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] Clojure and Hermes JavaScript engine) use this word to mean the act of pre-compiling the source language to VM specific bytecode.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] Angular (web framework) uses this word to mean converting its HTML template and TypeScript to JavaScript.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] In fact, since all static compilation is technically performed ahead of time, this particular wording is often used to emphasize examples where there are significant performance advantages over the act of such pre-compiling.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] The act of compiling Java to Java bytecode is hence rarely referred to as AOT since it is usually a requirement, not an optimization.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] Some programming languages with a managed code runtime that can be compiled to an intermediate representation use just-in-time (JIT) compiling.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] This briefly compiles intermediate code into machine code for a native run while the intermediate code is executing which may slow an application's performance.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] Ahead-of-time compiling eliminates the need for this step by occurring before execution rather than during execution.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] Ahead-of-time compiling for dynamically typed languages to native machine code or other static VM bytecode is possible in a limited number of cases only.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] For example, the High Performance Erlang Project (HiPE) AOT compiler for the language Erlang can do this because of advanced static type reconstruction techniques and type speculations.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] In most situations with fully AOT compiled programs and libraries, it is possible to remove part of a runtime environment, thus saving disk space, memory, battery life, and startup times (no JIT warmup phase), etc.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] Because of this, it can be useful in embedded or mobile devices.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] AOT compilers can perform complex and advanced code optimizations which in most cases of JITing will be considered much too costly.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] In contrast, AOT usually cannot perform some optimizations possible in JIT like runtime profile-guided optimization (PGO), pseudo-constant propagation, or indirect-virtual function inlining.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] AOT must compile to a target architecture while a JIT can compile the code to make the best use of the actual CPU it is running on, even years after the software has been released.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] Further, JIT compilers can speculatively optimize hot code by making assumptions on the code.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] The generated code can be deoptimized if a speculative assumption later proves wrong.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] Such operation slows the performance of the running software until code is optimized again by adaptive optimization.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] An AOT compiler cannot make such assumptions and needs to infer as much information as possible at compile time.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] It needs to resort to less specialized code because it cannot know what types will go through a method.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] Such problems can be alleviated by profile-guided optimizations.
[src:android-runtime-art/ahead-of-time-compilation] But even in this case, the generated code cannot be adapted dynamically to the changing runtime profile as a JIT compiler would do.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] At its core, the operating system is known as the **Android Open Source Project** (**AOSP**) and is free and open-source software (FOSS) primarily licensed under the Apache License.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Other Google services including Firebase Cloud Messaging, used for push notifications, are recommended for applications.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] While AOSP is free, the "Android" name and logo are trademarks of Google, who restrict the use of Android branding on "uncertified" products.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] The majority of smartphones based on AOSP run Google's ecosystem—which is known simply as Android—some with vendor-customized user interfaces and software suites, for example One UI.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Commercial products like micro consoles and virtual reality headset have also used Android.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Since 2011 Android has been the most used operating system worldwide on smartphones.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] It has the largest installed base of any operating system in the world with over three billion monthly active users and accounting for 46% of the global operating system market.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] In 2005, Rubin tried to negotiate deals with Samsung and HTC.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Shortly afterwards, Google acquired the company in July of that year for at least $50 million; this was Google's "best deal ever" according to Google's then-vice president of corporate development, David Lawee, in 2010.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Android's key employees, including Rubin, Miner, Sears, and White, joined Google as part of the acquisition.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Not much was known about the secretive Android Inc. at the time, with the company having provided few details other than that it was making software for mobile phones.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] At Google, the team led by Rubin developed a mobile device platform powered by the Linux kernel.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Google marketed the platform to handset makers and carriers on the promise of providing a flexible, upgradeable system.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Google had "lined up a series of hardware components and software partners and signaled to carriers that it was open to various degrees of cooperation".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Speculation about Google's intention to enter the mobile communications market continued to build through December 2006.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] An early prototype had a close resemblance to a BlackBerry phone, with no touchscreen and a physical QWERTY keyboard, but the arrival of Apple's 2007 iPhone meant that Android "had to go back to the drawing board".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Google later changed its Android specification documents to state that "Touchscreens will be supported", although "the Product was designed with the presence of discrete physical buttons as an assumption, therefore a touchscreen cannot completely replace physical buttons".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] By 2008, both Nokia and BlackBerry announced touch-based smartphones to rival the iPhone 3G, and Android's focus eventually switched to just touchscreens.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] The first commercially available smartphone running Android was the HTC Dream, also known as T-Mobile G1, announced on September 23, 2008.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Within a year, the Open Handset Alliance faced two other open source competitors, the Symbian Foundation and the LiMo Foundation, the latter also developing a Linux-based mobile operating system like Google.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] In September 2007, Google had filed several patent applications in the area of mobile telephony.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] On September 23, 2008, Android was introduced by Andy Rubin, Larry Page, Sergey Brin, Cole Brodman, Christopher Schlaeffer and Peter Chou at a press conference in a New York City subway station.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Since 2008, Android has seen numerous updates which have incrementally improved the operating system, adding new features and fixing bugs in previous releases.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] In 2010, Google launched its Nexus series of devices, a lineup in which Google partnered with different device manufacturers to produce new devices and introduce new Android versions.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] The series was described as having "played a pivotal role in Android's history by introducing new software iterations and hardware standards across the board", and became known for its "bloat-free" software with "timely ... updates".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] At its developer conference in May 2013, Google announced a special version of the Samsung Galaxy S4, where, instead of using Samsung's own Android customization, the phone ran "stock Android" and was promised to receive new system updates fast.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] The device would become the start of the Google Play edition program, and was followed by other devices, including the HTC One Google Play edition, and Moto G Google Play edition.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] In 2015, *Ars Technica* wrote that "Earlier this week, the last of the Google Play edition Android phones in Google's online storefront were listed as "no longer available for sale" and that "Now they're all gone, and it looks a whole lot like the program has wrapped up".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] From 2008 to 2013, Hugo Barra served as product spokesperson, representing Android at press conferences and Google I/O, Google's annual developer-focused conference.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] He left Google in August 2013 to join Chinese phone maker Xiaomi.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Less than six months earlier, Google's then-CEO Larry Page announced in a blog post that Andy Rubin had moved from the Android division to take on new projects at Google, and that Sundar Pichai would become the new Android lead.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Pichai himself would eventually switch positions, becoming the new CEO of Google in August 2015 following the company's restructure into the Alphabet conglomerate, making Hiroshi Lockheimer the new head of Android.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] On Android 4.4, *KitKat*, shared writing access to MicroSD memory cards has been locked for user-installed applications, to which only the dedicated directories with respective package names, located inside `Android/data/`, remained writeable.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Writing access has been reinstated with Android 5 *Lollipop* through the backwards-incompatible *Google Storage Access Framework* interface.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] In June 2014, Google announced Android One, a set of "hardware reference models" that would "allow [device makers] to easily create high-quality phones at low costs", designed for consumers in developing countries.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] In September, Google announced the first set of Android One phones for release in India.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] However, *Recode* reported in June 2015 that the project was "a disappointment", citing "reluctant consumers and manufacturing partners" and "misfires from the search company that has never quite cracked hardware".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Plans to relaunch Android One surfaced in August 2015, with Africa announced as the next location for the program a week later.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] A report from *The Information* in January 2017 stated that Google is expanding its low-cost Android One program into the United States, although *The Verge* notes that the company will presumably not produce the actual devices itself.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Google introduced the Pixel and Pixel XL smartphones in October 2016, marketed as being the first phones made by Google, and exclusively featured certain software features, such as the Google Assistant, before wider rollout.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] The Pixel phones replaced the Nexus series, with a new generation of Pixel phones launched in October 2017.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] In May 2019, the operating system became entangled in the trade war between China and the United States involving Huawei, which, like many other tech firms, had become dependent on access to the Android platform.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] In the summer of 2019, Huawei announced it would create an alternative operating system to Android known as Harmony OS, and has filed for intellectual property rights across major global markets.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Under such sanctions Huawei has long-term plans to replace Android in 2022 with the new operating system, as Harmony OS was originally designed for internet of things devices, rather than for smartphones and tablets.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] On August 22, 2019, it was announced that Android "Q" would officially be branded as Android 10, ending the historic practice of naming major versions after desserts.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Google stated that these names were not "inclusive" to international users (due either to the aforementioned foods not being internationally known, or being difficult to pronounce in some languages).
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] On the same day, *Android Police* reported that Google had commissioned a statue of a giant number "10" to be installed in the lobby of the developers' new office.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Android 10 was released on September 3, 2019, to Google Pixel phones first.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] In late 2021, some users reported that they were unable to dial emergency services.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] The problem was caused by a combination of bugs in Android and in the Microsoft Teams app; both companies released updates addressing the issue.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] On December 12, 2024, Google announced Android XR.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] It is a new operating system developed by Google, designed for virtual reality and augmented reality devices, such as VR headsets and smart glasses.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] It was built in collaboration with Samsung and Qualcomm.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] The platform is also focused on supporting developers with tools like ARCore and Unity to build applications for upcoming XR devices.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] In March 2025, Google announced its plans to consolidate Android development to internal sources.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] While public developers will no longer be able to contribute, the Android source will still be published.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Android's default user interface is mainly based on direct manipulation, using touch inputs that loosely correspond to real-world actions, like swiping, tapping, pinching, and reverse pinching to manipulate on-screen objects, along with a virtual keyboard.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Game controllers and full-size physical keyboards are supported via Bluetooth or USB.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] The response to user input is designed to be immediate and provides a fluid touch interface, often using the vibration capabilities of the device to provide haptic feedback to the user.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Android devices boot to the home screen, the primary navigation and information "hub" on Android devices, analogous to the desktop found on personal computers.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Android home screens are typically made up of app icons and widgets; app icons launch the associated app, whereas widgets display live, auto-updating content, such as a weather forecast, the user's email inbox, or a news ticker directly on the home screen.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] A home screen may be made up of several pages, between which the user can swipe back and forth.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Third-party apps available on Google Play and other app stores can extensively re-theme the home screen, and even mimic the look of other operating systems, such as Windows Phone.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Most manufacturers customize the look and features of their Android devices to differentiate themselves from their competitors.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Along the top of the screen is a status bar, showing information about the device and its connectivity.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] This status bar can be pulled (swiped) down to reveal a notification screen where apps display important information or updates, as well as quick access to system controls and toggles such as display brightness, connectivity settings (WiFi, Bluetooth, cellular data), audio mode, and flashlight.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Vendors may implement extended settings such as the ability to adjust the flashlight brightness.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Notifications are "short, timely, and relevant information about your app when it's not in use", and when tapped, users are directed to a screen inside the app relating to the notification.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Beginning with Android 4.1 "Jelly Bean", "expandable notifications" allow the user to tap an icon on the notification in order for it to expand and display more information and possible app actions right from the notification.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] An "All Apps" screen lists all installed applications, with the ability for users to drag an app from the list onto the home screen.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] The app list may be accessed using a gesture or a button, depending on the Android version.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] A "Recents" screen, also known as "Overview", lets users switch between recently used apps.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] The recent list may appear side-by-side or overlapping, depending on the Android version and manufacturer.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Many early Android OS smartphones were equipped with a dedicated search button for quick access to a web search engine and individual apps' internal search feature.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] More recent devices typically allow the former through a long press or swipe away from the home button.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] The dedicated option key, also known as menu key, and its on-screen simulation, is no longer supported since Android version 10.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Google recommends mobile application developers to locate menus within the user interface.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] On more recent phones, its place is occupied by a task key used to access the list of recently used apps when actuated.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Depending on device, its long press may simulate a menu button press or engage split screen view, the latter of which is the default behaviour since stock Android version 7.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Native support for split screen view has been added in stock Android version 7.0 *Nougat*.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] The earliest vendor-customized Android-based smartphones known to have featured a split-screen view mode are the 2012 Samsung Galaxy S3 and Note 2, the former of which received this feature with the *premium suite* upgrade delivered in TouchWiz with Android 4.1 Jelly Bean.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Android has supported a rudimentary Desktop Mode in developer options.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] A native desktop mode was rolled out in March 2026 to Pixel devices from the Pixel 8 onward; tablets received it with Android 16 QPR3, with the intention to roll this feature out to more devices in the future.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Most Android devices come with preinstalled Google apps including Gmail, Google Maps, Google Chrome, YouTube, Google TV, and others.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Java is still supported (originally the only option for user-space programs, and is often mixed with Kotlin), as is C++.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Java or other JVM languages, such as Kotlin, may be combined with C/C++, together with a choice of non-default runtimes that allow better C++ support.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] The SDK includes a comprehensive set of development tools, including a debugger, software libraries, a handset emulator based on QEMU, documentation, sample code, and tutorials.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Initially, Google's supported integrated development environment (IDE) was Eclipse using the Android Development Tools (ADT) plugin; in December 2014, Google released Android Studio, based on IntelliJ IDEA, as its primary IDE for Android application development.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Other development tools are available, including a native development kit (NDK) for applications or extensions in C or C++, Google App Inventor, a visual environment for novice programmers, and various cross platform mobile web applications frameworks.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] In January 2014, Google unveiled a framework based on Apache Cordova for porting Chrome HTML 5 web applications to Android, wrapped in a native application shell.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Additionally, Firebase was acquired by Google in 2014 that provides helpful tools for app and web developers.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Google Play Store is the primary application store installed on Android devices that comply with Google's compatibility requirements and license the Google Mobile Services software.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Google Play Store allows users to browse, download and update applications published by Google and third-party developers; as of January 2021, there are more than three million applications available for Android in Play Store.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] As of July 2013, 50 billion application installations had been performed.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Some carriers offer direct carrier billing for Google Play application purchases, where the cost of the application is added to the user's monthly bill.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] As of May 2017, there are over one billion active users a month for Gmail, Android, Chrome, Google Play and Maps.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Examples of these third-party stores have included the Amazon Appstore, GetJar, and SlideMe.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] F-Droid, another alternative marketplace, seeks to only provide applications that are distributed under free and open source licenses.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] In October 2020, Google removed several Android applications from Play Store, as they were identified breaching its data collection rules.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] The firm was informed by International Digital Accountability Council (IDAC) that apps for children like *Number Coloring*, *Princess Salon* and *Cats & Cosplay*, with collective downloads of 20 million, were violating Google's policies.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] At the Windows 11 announcement event in June 2021, Microsoft showcased the new Windows Subsystem for Android (WSA) to enable support for the Android Open Source Project (AOSP), but it has since been deprecated.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] It was intended to allow users to run Android apps and games on their Windows 11 desktop.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Microsoft ended WSA support on March 5, 2025.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] The storage of Android devices can be expanded using secondary devices such as SD cards.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Android recognizes two types of secondary storage: *portable* storage (which is used by default), and *adoptable* storage.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Portable storage is treated as an external storage device.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Adoptable storage, introduced on Android 6.0, allows the internal storage of the device to be spanned with the SD card, treating it as an extension of the internal storage.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] This has the disadvantage of preventing the memory card from being used with another device unless it is reformatted.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Android 4.4 introduced the Storage Access Framework (SAF), a set of APIs for accessing files on the device's filesystem.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] As of Android 11, Android has required apps to conform to a data privacy policy known as *scoped storage*, under which apps may only automatically have access to certain directories (such as those for pictures, music, and video), and app-specific directories they have created themselves.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Apps are required to use the SAF to access any other part of the filesystem.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Since Android devices are usually battery-powered, Android is designed to manage processes to keep power consumption at a minimum.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] When an application is not in use the system suspends its operation so that, while available for immediate use rather than closed, it does not use battery power or CPU resources.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Android manages the applications stored in memory automatically: when memory is low, the system will begin invisibly and automatically closing inactive processes, starting with those that have been inactive for the longest amount of time.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Lifehacker reported in 2011 that third-party task-killer applications were doing more harm than good.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] "App's Not Responding"), prevent a Bluetooth audio client from controlling the system volume ("Disable absolute volume"), and adjust the duration of transition animations or deactivate them completely to speed up navigation.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Developer options are initially hidden since Android 4.2 "Jelly Bean", but can be enabled by actuating the operating system's build number in the device information seven times.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Hiding developers options again requires deleting user data for the "Settings" app, possibly resetting some other preferences, or in recent Android versions, turning off the Developer options master switch.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] The main hardware platform for Android is 64-bit ARM (i.e. the ARMv8-A architecture) and the 32-bit ARMv7-A architecture, with x86-64 and the 32-bit x86 architectures also being officially supported in later versions of Android.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] The unofficial Android-x86 project provided support for x86 architectures ahead of the official support.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Since 2012, Android devices with Intel processors began to appear, including phones and tablets.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] While gaining support for 64-bit platforms, Android was first made to run on 64-bit x86 and then on ARM64.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] An unofficial experimental port of the operating system to 64-bit RISC-V architecture was released in 2021.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Requirements for the minimum amount of RAM for smartphones running Android 15 range from 4 GB of RAM for full Android to 2 GB, in which case the smartphone manufacturers must use the Android Go Edition.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Android supports all versions of OpenGL ES and Vulkan (and version 1.1 available for some devices).
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Android devices incorporate many optional hardware components, including still or video cameras, GPS, orientation sensors, dedicated gaming controls, accelerometers, gyroscopes, barometers, magnetometers, proximity sensors, pressure sensors, thermometers, and touchscreens.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Some hardware components are not required, but became standard in certain classes of devices, such as smartphones, and additional requirements apply if they are present.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Some other hardware was initially required, but those requirements have been relaxed or eliminated altogether.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] For example, as Android was developed initially as a phone OS, hardware such as microphones were required, while over time the phone function became optional.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Android used to require an autofocus camera, which was relaxed to a fixed-focus camera if present at all, since the camera was dropped as a requirement entirely when Android started to be used on set-top boxes.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] In addition to running on smartphones and tablets, several vendors run Android natively on regular PC hardware with a keyboard and mouse.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] In addition to their availability on commercially available hardware, similar PC hardware-friendly versions of Android are freely available from the Android-x86 project, including customized Android 4.4.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Using the Android emulator that is part of the Android SDK, or third-party emulators, Android can also run non-natively on x86 architectures.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Chinese companies are building a PC and mobile operating system, based on Android, to "compete directly with Microsoft Windows and Google Android".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] The Chinese Academy of Engineering noted that "more than a dozen" companies were customizing Android following a Chinese ban on the use of Windows 8 on government PCs.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Android runs on a wide variety of devices such as smartphones, tablets, cars, computers, smart watches, and smart TVs.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] However, the vast majority of Android-powered devices are smartphones.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] Unlike its two main competitors in the mobile operating system space, namely iOS and HarmonyOS, Android devices are made by many different original equipment manufacturers.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p01] These OEMs include Samsung, Xiaomi, Vivo, Oppo, iQOO, OnePlus, Honor, Google, Sony, Lenovo, Sharp, Realme, Nothing, and Tecno.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Android is developed by Google until the latest changes and updates are ready to be released, at which point the source code is made available to the Android Open Source Project (AOSP), an open source initiative led by Google.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The first source code release happened as part of the initial release in 2007.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] All releases are under the Apache License.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The AOSP code can be found with minimal modifications on select devices, mainly the former Nexus and current Android One series of devices.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] However, most original equipment manufacturers (OEMs) customize the source code to run on their hardware.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Android's source code does not contain the device drivers, often proprietary, that are needed for certain hardware components, and does not contain the source code of Google Play Services, which many apps depend on.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] As a result, most Android devices, including Google's own, ship with a combination of free and open source and proprietary software, with the software required for accessing Google services falling into the latter category.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In response to this, there are some projects that build complete operating systems based on AOSP as free software, the first being CyanogenMod (see section Open-source community below).
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Google provides annual Android releases, both for factory installation in new devices, and for over-the-air updates to existing devices.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The extensive variation of hardware in Android devices has caused significant delays for software upgrades and security patches.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Each upgrade has had to be specifically tailored, a time- and resource-consuming process.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Except for devices within the Google Nexus and Pixel brands, updates have often arrived months after the release of the new version, or not at all.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Manufacturers often prioritize their newest devices and leave old ones behind.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Additional delays can be introduced by wireless carriers who, after receiving updates from manufacturers, further customize Android to their needs and conduct extensive testing on their networks before sending out the upgrade.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] There are also situations in which upgrades are impossible due to a manufacturer not updating necessary drivers.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The lack of after-sale support from manufacturers and carriers has been widely criticized by consumer groups and the technology media.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Some commentators have noted that the industry has a financial incentive not to upgrade their devices, as the lack of updates for existing devices fuels the purchase of newer ones, an attitude described as "insulting".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] *The Guardian* complained that the method of distribution for updates is complicated only because manufacturers and carriers have designed it that way.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In 2011, Google partnered with a number of industry players to announce an "Android Update Alliance", pledging to deliver timely updates for every device for 18 months after its release; however, there has not been another official word about that alliance since its announcement.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In 2012, Google began de-coupling certain aspects of the operating system (particularly its central applications) so they could be updated through the Google Play store independently of the OS.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] One of those components, Google Play Services, is a closed-source system-level process providing APIs for Google services, installed automatically on nearly all devices running Android 2.2 "Froyo" and higher.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] With these changes, Google can add new system functions and update apps without having to distribute an upgrade to the operating system itself.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] As a result, Android 4.2 and 4.3 "Jelly Bean" contained relatively fewer user-facing changes, focusing more on minor changes and platform improvements.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] HTC's then-executive Jason Mackenzie called monthly security updates "unrealistic" in 2015, and Google was trying to persuade carriers to exclude security patches from the full testing procedures.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] As stated by *Bloomberg*: "As smartphones get more capable, complex and hackable, having the latest software work closely with the hardware is increasingly important".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Hiroshi Lockheimer, the Android lead, admitted that "It's not an ideal situation", further commenting that the lack of updates is "the weakest link on security on Android".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Wireless carriers were described in the report as the "most challenging discussions", due to their slow approval time while testing on their networks, despite some carriers, including Verizon Wireless and Sprint Corporation, already shortening their approval times.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In a further effort for persuasion, Google shared a list of top phone makers measured by updated devices with its Android partners, and is considering making the list public.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Mike Chan, co-founder of phone maker Nextbit and former Android developer, said that "The best way to solve this problem is a massive re-architecture of the operating system", "or Google could invest in training manufacturers and carriers 'to be good Android citizens'".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In May 2017, with the announcement of Android 8.0, Google introduced Project Treble, a major re-architect of the Android OS framework designed to make it easier, faster, and less costly for manufacturers to update devices to newer versions of Android.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Project Treble separates the vendor implementation (device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new "vendor interface".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In Android 7.0 and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists, so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of the operating system.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In May 2019, with the announcement of Android 10, Google introduced Project Mainline to simplify and expedite delivery of updates to the Android ecosystem.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Project Mainline enables updates to core OS components through the Google Play Store.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] As a result, important security and performance improvements that previously needed to be part of full OS updates can be downloaded and installed as easily as an app update.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Google reported rolling out new amendments in Android 12 aimed at making the use of third-party application stores easier.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] This announcement rectified the concerns reported regarding the development of Android apps, including a fight over an alternative in-app payment system and difficulties faced by businesses moving online because of COVID-19.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Android's kernel is based on the Linux kernel's long-term support (LTS) branches.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The actual kernel depends on the individual device.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Android's variant of the Linux kernel has further architectural changes that are implemented by Google outside the typical Linux kernel development cycle, such as the inclusion of components like device trees, ashmem, ION, and different out of memory (OOM) handling.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Certain features that Google contributed back to the Linux kernel, notably a power management feature called "wakelocks", were initially rejected by mainline kernel developers partly because they felt that Google did not show any intent to maintain its own code.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Google engineer Patrick Brady once stated in the company's developer conference that "Android is not Linux", with *Computerworld* adding that "Let me make it simple for you, without Linux, there is no Android".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] *Ars Technica* wrote that "Although Android is built on top of the Linux kernel, the platform has very little in common with the conventional desktop Linux stack".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In August 2011, Linus Torvalds said that "eventually Android and Linux would come back to a common kernel, but it will probably not be for four to five years".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In December 2011, Greg Kroah-Hartman announced the start of Android Mainlining Project, which aims to put some Android drivers, patches and features back into the Linux kernel, starting in Linux 3.3.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Linux included the autosleep and wakelocks capabilities in the 3.5 kernel, after many previous attempts at a merger.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The interfaces are the same but the upstream Linux implementation allows for two different suspend modes: to memory (the traditional suspend that Android uses), and to disk (hibernate, as it is known on the desktop).
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Google maintains a public code repository that contains their experimental work to re-base Android off the latest stable Linux versions.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Android is a Linux distribution according to the Linux Foundation, Google's open-source chief Chris DiBona, and several journalists.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Others, such as Google engineer Patrick Brady, say that Android is not Linux in the traditional Unix-like Linux distribution sense; Android does not include the GNU C Library (it uses Bionic as an alternative C library) and some other components typically found in Linux distributions.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] With the release of Android Oreo in 2017, Google began to require that devices shipped with new SoCs had Linux kernel version 4.4 or newer, for security reasons.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Existing devices upgraded to Oreo, and new products launched with older SoCs, were exempt from this rule.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The flash storage on Android devices is split into several partitions, such as `/system/` for the operating system itself, and `/data/` for user data and application installations.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In contrast to typical desktop Linux distributions, Android device owners are not given root access to the operating system and sensitive partitions such as `/system/` are partially read-only.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] However, root access can be obtained by exploiting security flaws in Android, which is used frequently by the open-source community to enhance the capabilities and customizability of their devices, but also by malicious parties to install viruses and malware.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The unlocking process resets the system to factory state, erasing all user data.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Proprietary frameworks like Samsung Knox limit or block attempts at rooting.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Google's Play Integrity API allows developers to check for any signs of tampering, although the fairness of the tests have been criticized.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] On top of the Linux kernel, there are the middleware, libraries and APIs written in C, and application software running on an application framework which includes Java-compatible libraries.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Development of the Linux kernel continues independently of Android's other source code projects.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Android uses Android Runtime (ART) as its runtime environment (introduced in version 4.4), which uses ahead-of-time (AOT) compilation to entirely compile the application bytecode into machine code upon the installation of an application.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In Android 4.4, ART was an experimental feature and not enabled by default; it became the only runtime option in the next major version of Android, 5.0.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In versions no longer supported, until version 5.0 when ART took over, Android previously used Dalvik as a process virtual machine with trace-based just-in-time (JIT) compilation to run Dalvik "dex-code" (Dalvik Executable), which is usually translated from the Java bytecode.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Following the trace-based JIT principle, in addition to interpreting the majority of application code, Dalvik performs the compilation and native execution of select frequently executed code segments ("traces") each time an application is launched.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] For its Java library, the Android platform uses a subset of the now discontinued Apache Harmony project.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In December 2015, Google announced that the next version of Android would switch to a Java implementation based on the OpenJDK project.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Android's standard C library, Bionic, was developed by Google specifically for Android, as a derivation of the BSD's standard C library code.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Bionic itself has been designed with several major features specific to the Linux kernel.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The main benefits of using Bionic instead of the GNU C Library (glibc) or uClibc are its smaller runtime footprint, and optimization for low-frequency CPUs.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] At the same time, Bionic is licensed under the terms of the BSD licence, which Google finds more suitable for the Android's overall licensing model.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Aiming for a different licensing model, toward the end of 2012, Google switched the Bluetooth stack in Android from the GPL-licensed BlueZ to the Apache-licensed BlueDroid.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] A new Bluetooth stack, called Gabeldorsche, was developed to try to fix the bugs in the BlueDroid implementation.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Android does not have a native X Window System by default, nor does it support the full set of standard GNU libraries.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] This made it difficult to port existing Linux applications or libraries to Android, until version r5 of the Android Native Development Kit brought support for applications written completely in C or C++.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Libraries written in C may also be used in applications by injection of a small shim and usage of the JNI.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In current versions of Android, "Toybox", a collection of command-line utilities (mostly for use by apps, as Android does not provide a command-line interface by default), is used (since the release of Marshmallow) replacing a similar "Toolbox" collection found in previous Android versions.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Community releases often come pre-rooted and contain modifications not provided by the original vendor, such as the ability to overclock or over/undervolt the device's processor, or security enhancements beyond what is included in the stock OS.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] CyanogenMod was the most widely used community firmware; after its abrupt discontinuation in 2016, a community fork known as LineageOS was established as a spiritual continuation of the project.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Historically, device manufacturers and mobile carriers have typically been unsupportive of third-party firmware development.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Manufacturers express concern about improper functioning of devices running unofficial software and the support costs resulting from this.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Moreover, modified firmware such as CyanogenMod sometimes offer features, such as tethering, for which carriers would otherwise charge a premium.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] As a result, technical obstacles including locked bootloaders and restricted access to root permissions are common in many devices.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] However, despite manufacturer acceptance, some carriers in the US still require that phones are locked down.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Android was also ported by the community to Apple's iPhone, iPad and iPod touch devices as a consequence of porting the Linux kernel on Apple devices.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In 2010, OpeniBoot and subsequently iDroid were released to allow dual booting iOS and Android 2.3.3 'Gingerbread' on jailbroken iPhone or iPod Touch devices, which was ultimately declared as discontinued in 2012.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In 2020, David Wang under his company Corellium released Project Sandcastle which made Android run on the iPhone 7.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Internally, Android identifies each supported device by its **device codename**, a short string, which may or may not be similar to the model name used in marketing the device.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] For example, the device codename of the Pixel smartphone is *sailfish*.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The device codename is usually not visible to the end user, but is important for determining compatibility with modified Android versions.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] It is sometimes also mentioned in articles discussing a device, because it allows to distinguish different hardware variants of a device, even if the manufacturer offers them under the same name.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The device codename is available to running applications under `android.os.Build.DEVICE`.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In 2020, Google launched the Android Partner Vulnerability Initiative to improve the security of Android.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] They also formed an Android security team.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Research from security company Trend Micro lists premium service abuse as the most common type of Android malware, where text messages are sent from infected phones to premium-rate telephone numbers without the consent or even knowledge of the user.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Other malware displays unwanted and intrusive advertisements on the device, or sends personal information to unauthorised third parties.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Google maintains that dangerous malware is actually extremely rare, and a survey conducted by F-Secure showed that only 0.5% of Android malware reported had come from the Google Play store.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Analysis of data traffic by popular smartphones running variants of Android found substantial by-default data collection and sharing with no opt-out by this pre-installed software.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Both of these issues are not addressed or cannot be addressed by security patches.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] They were reportedly able to read almost all smartphone information, including SMS, location, emails, and notes.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] GCHQ has, according to *The Guardian*, a wiki-style guide of different apps and advertising networks, and the different data that can be siphoned from each.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Later that week, the Finnish Angry Birds developer Rovio announced that it was reconsidering its relationships with its advertising platforms in the light of these revelations, and called upon the wider industry to do the same.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The documents revealed a further effort by the intelligence agencies to intercept Google Maps searches and queries submitted from Android and other smartphones to collect location information in bulk.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Leaked documents codenamed Vault 7 and dated from 2013 to 2016, detail the capabilities of the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) to perform electronic surveillance and cyber warfare, including the ability to compromise the operating systems of most smartphones (including Android).
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In August 2015, Google announced that devices in the Google Nexus series would begin to receive monthly security patches.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Ron Amadeo of *Ars Technica* wrote also in August 2015 that "Android was originally designed, above all else, to be widely adopted.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] As such, security has become a big issue.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Android still uses a software update chain-of-command designed back when the Android ecosystem had zero devices to update, and it just doesn't work".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Following news of Google's monthly schedule, some manufacturers, including Samsung and LG, promised to issue monthly security updates, but, as noted by Jerry Hildenbrand in *Android Central* in February 2016, "instead we got a few updates on specific versions of a small handful of models.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] They also wrote that "About half of devices in use at the end of 2016 had not received a platform security update in the previous year", stating that their work would continue to focus on streamlining the security updates program for easier deployment by manufacturers.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Furthermore, in a comment to *TechCrunch*, Ludwig stated that the wait time for security updates had been reduced from "six to nine weeks down to just a few days", with 78% of flagship devices in North America being up-to-date on security at the end of 2016.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-priced devices.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] However, the open-source nature of Android allows security contractors to take existing devices and adapt them for highly secure uses.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] For example, Samsung has worked with General Dynamics through their Open Kernel Labs acquisition to rebuild *Jelly Bean* on top of their hardened microvisor for the "Knox" project.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Android smartphones have the ability to report the location of Wi-Fi access points, encountered as phone users move around, to build databases containing the physical locations of hundreds of millions of such access points.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] These databases form electronic maps to locate smartphones, allowing them to run apps like Foursquare, Google Latitude, Facebook Places, and to deliver location-based ads.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Third party monitoring software such as TaintDroid, an academic research-funded project, can, in some cases, detect when personal information is being sent from applications to remote servers.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In 2018, Norwegian security firm Promon has unearthed a serious Android security hole which can be exploited to steal login credentials, access messages, and track location, which could be found in all versions of Android, including Android 10.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The vulnerability came by exploiting a bug in the multitasking system enabling a malicious app to overlay legitimate apps with fake login screens that users are not aware of when handing in security credentials.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Users can also be tricked into granting additional permissions to the malicious apps, which later enable them to perform various nefarious activities, including intercepting texts or calls and stealing banking credentials.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] *Avast Threat Labs* also discovered that many pre-installed apps on several hundred new Android devices contain dangerous malware and adware.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Some of the preinstalled malware can commit ad fraud or even take over its host device.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In 2020, the Which? watchdog reported that more than a billion Android devices released in 2012 or earlier, which was 40% of Android devices worldwide, were at risk of being hacked.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] This conclusion stemmed from the fact that no security updates were issued for the Android versions below 7.0 in 2019.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Which? collaborated with the AV Comparatives anti-virus lab to infect five phone models with malware, and it succeeded in each case.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Google refused to comment on the watchdog's speculations.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] On August 5, 2020, Twitter published a blog urging its users to update their applications to the latest version with regards to a security concern that allowed others to access direct messages.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] A hacker could easily use the "Android system permissions" to fetch the account credentials in order to do so.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The security issue is only with Android 8 (Android Oreo) and Android 9 (Android Pie).
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Twitter confirmed that updating the app will restrict such practices.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Android applications run in a sandbox, an isolated area of the system that does not have access to the rest of the system's resources, unless access permissions are explicitly granted by the user when the application is installed, however this may not be possible for pre-installed apps.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] It is not possible, for example, to turn off the microphone access of the pre-installed camera app without disabling the camera completely.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] This is valid also in Android versions 7 and 8.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Since February 2012, Google has used its Google Bouncer malware scanner to watch over and scan apps available in the Google Play store.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] A "Verify Apps" feature was introduced in November 2012, as part of the Android 4.2 "Jelly Bean" operating system version, to scan all apps, both from Google Play and from third-party sources, for malicious behaviour.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Originally only doing so during installation, Verify Apps received an update in 2014 to "constantly" scan apps, and in 2017 the feature was made visible to users through a menu in Settings.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In former Android versions, before installing an application, the Google Play store displayed a list of the requirements an app needs to function.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] After reviewing these permissions, the user could choose to accept or refuse them, installing the application only if they accepted.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In Android 6.0 "Marshmallow", the permissions system was changed; apps are no longer automatically granted all of their specified permissions at installation time.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] An opt-in system is used instead, in which users are prompted to grant or deny individual permissions to an app when they are needed for the first time.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Applications remember the grants, which can be revoked by the user at any time.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Pre-installed apps, however, are not always part of this approach.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In some cases it may not be possible to deny certain permissions to pre-installed apps, nor be possible to disable them.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The Google Play Services app cannot be uninstalled, nor disabled.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Any force stop attempt results in the app restarting itself.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The new permissions model is used only by applications developed for Marshmallow using its software development kit (SDK), and older apps will continue to use the previous all-or-nothing approach.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Permissions can still be revoked for those apps, though this might prevent them from working properly, and a warning is displayed to that effect.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In September 2014, Jason Nova of *Android Authority* reported on a study by the German security company Fraunhofer AISEC in antivirus software and malware threats on Android.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Nova wrote that "The Android operating system deals with software packages by sandboxing them; this does not allow applications to list the directory contents of other apps to keep the system safe.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] By not allowing the antivirus to list the directories of other apps after installation, applications that show no inherent suspicious behavior when downloaded are cleared as safe.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] If then later on parts of the app are activated that turn out to be malicious, the antivirus will have no way to know since it is inside the app and out of the antivirus' jurisdiction".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In August 2013, Google announced Android Device Manager (renamed Find My Device in May 2017), a service that allows users to remotely track, locate, and wipe their Android device, with an Android app for the service released in December.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In December 2016, Google introduced a Trusted Contacts app, letting users request location-tracking of loved ones during emergencies.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In 2020, Trusted Contacts was shut down and the location-sharing feature rolled into Google Maps.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] On October 8, 2018, Google announced new Google Play store requirements to combat oversharing of potentially sensitive information, including call and text logs.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The issue stems from the fact that many apps request permissions to access users' personal information, even if this information is not needed for the app to function, and some users unquestionably grant these permissions.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Alternatively, a permission might be listed in the app manifest as required (as opposed to optional) and the app would not install unless user grants the permission; users can withdraw any, even required, permissions from any app in the device settings after app installation, but few users do this.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Google promised to work with developers and create exceptions if their apps require phone or SMS permissions for core functionality.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The enforcement of this policy began on January 6, 2019, 90 days after its announcement.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Furthermore, Google announced a new "target API level requirement" (`targetSdkVersion` in manifest) of at least Android 8.0 (API level 26) for all new apps and app updates.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The API level requirement was intended to combat the practice of app developers bypassing some permission screens by specifying early Android versions that had a coarser permission model.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The Android Open Source Project implements a verified boot chain with intentions to verify that executed code, such as the kernel or bootloader, comes from an official source instead of a malicious actor.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] This implementation establishes a full chain of trust, as it initially starts at a hardware level.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Subsequently, the boot loader is verified and system partitions such as `system` and `vendor` are checked for integrity.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Furthermore, this process verifies that a previous version of Android has not been installed.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] This effectively provides rollback protection, which mitigates exploits that are similar to a downgrade attack.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Android (all supported versions, as far back as version 4.4 of the Android Open Source Project) has the option to provide a verified boot chain with `dm-verity`.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] This is a feature in the Linux kernel that allows for transparent integrity checking of block devices.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] This feature is designed to mitigate persistent rootkits.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Dependence on proprietary Google Play Services and customizations added on top of the operating system by vendors who license Android from Google is causing privacy concerns.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In 2019, Google was fined €50 million by the French CNIL for a lack of information regarding their users.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Two years later, in 2021, researcher Douglas Leith, using a sort of data interception, showed that several data are sent from Android device to Google's servers, even when the phone is sleeping (IDLE) with no Google account registered into it.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Several Google applications send data, such as Chrome, Message or Docs, however YouTube is the only one to add a unique identifier data.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In 2022, Leith showed that an Android phone sent various data related to communications, including phone and text messages to Google.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Timestamp, sender and receiver, plus several other data, are sent to Google Play Services infrastructure, even if the "Usage and Diag" feature is disabled.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Those data are marked with a Unique Identifier of an Android device, and do not comply with GDPR.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In 2022, Google was sanctioned A$60 Million (US$40 million) by the Federal Court of Australia for misleading consumers about Google's collection of location data from Android phones.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The ACCC estimates that around 1.3 million Australian Google account owners were impacted by this design.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Google has since taken remedial steps to address the behavior.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] A similar case to the 2019 French case regarding location tracking, was brought in the U.S. in a privacy lawsuit filed by a coalition of attorneys general from 40 U.S. states.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] A penalty of USD 391 Million was agreed between Google and the DoJ.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The New York Times released at that time a long-term investigation about those privacy concerns.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Android devices, particularly low-end and mid-range models, have been criticized for their short software support lifespans.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Starting in the 2010s, many users found that their devices received only one or two major updates and a limited number of security patches.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] This lack of long-term support stemmed from manufacturers' unwillingness to invest in costly software upgrades, which were often tied to contractual agreements with chipset suppliers like Qualcomm.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] As a result, Android developed a reputation for rapid device obsolescence.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] To address this concern, Google introduced Project Treble, a framework designed to streamline the development and deployment of Android updates via Google Play Services, reducing manufacturers' involvement in the update process.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] However, for many devices, significant improvements were still limited by the chipset manufacturers.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Fairphone, a company focused on sustainability, explained that its inability to extend software support was due to Qualcomm's policies rather than its own.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Apple executives also highlighted Android's fragmented update ecosystem in their critiques of the platform, while quietly admitting that Qualcomm had also made it difficult for them to offer updates to the iPhone.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In response to this problem, several community-driven initiatives emerged to provide alternative operating systems for unsupported devices including LineageOS, Sailfish OS, Ubuntu Touch, and PostmarketOS.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Starting in 2022, Samsung, the largest Android smartphone manufacturer, announced extended software support from previous two years, first to four years, followed by five years in 2023 and six years in 2024.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Shortly thereafter, Qualcomm followed suit, offering extending support timelines for OEM building phones with its chipsets, first to seven years in 2024, followed by eight years in 2025.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] However, the support commitment was only for its most powerful chipsets, and did not make a similar commitment for chipsets used in low-end and mid-range phones.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] These changes bring Samsung and potentially some Qualcomm-powered devices closer to competing platforms, such as Apple, whose iPhones have received four to eight years of support.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] In 2025, Google announced that all developers must register under its developer program in order to distribute applications on certified Android phones, whether it is done through the Play Store, sideloaded APKs, or third-party stores like F-Droid, citing security reasons.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] This measure will be effective starting September 2026.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] The measure will not directly affect degoogled custom ROMs, such as GrapheneOS.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] Google has faced a backlash by experts, developers, activists, lawyers and other groups, which founded the Keep Android Open initiative to raise awareness and signed an open letter urging Google to rescind the policy.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] They argue that Google will become a gatekeeper as it will be able to decide which apps can be installed and which others will not, provided that "sideloading" will be considerably tampered by the measure (at least 9 steps needed and it would imply waiting 24 hours before an install).
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p02] They also criticize that it creates "an ever-expanding pathway to internet censorship" alleging more centralization of power.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] The source code for Android is open-source: it is developed in private by Google, with the source code released publicly when a new version of Android is released.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Google publishes most of the code (including network and telephony stacks) under the non-copyleft Apache License version 2.0. which allows modification and redistribution.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] The license does not grant rights to the "Android" trademark, so device manufacturers and wireless carriers have to license it from Google under individual contracts.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Associated Linux kernel changes are released under the copyleft GNU General Public License version 2, developed by the Open Handset Alliance, with the source code publicly available at all times.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] The only Android release which was not immediately made available as source code was the tablet-only 3.0 *Honeycomb* release.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] The reason, according to Andy Rubin in an official Android blog post, was because *Honeycomb* was rushed for production of the Motorola Xoom, and they did not want third parties creating a "really bad user experience" by attempting to put onto smartphones a version of Android intended for tablets.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] These applications must be licensed from Google by device makers, and can only be shipped on devices which meet its compatibility guidelines and other requirements.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Custom, certified distributions of Android produced by manufacturers (such as Samsung Experience) may also replace certain stock Android apps with their own proprietary variants and add additional software not included in the stock Android operating system.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] With the advent of the Google Pixel line of devices, Google itself has also made specific Android features timed or permanent exclusives to the Pixel series.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] There may also be "binary blob" drivers required for certain hardware components in the device.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] The best known fully open source Android services are the LineageOS distribution and MicroG which acts as an open source replacement of Google Play Services.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In both cases, the use of closed-source software causes the system to become vulnerable to backdoors.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] It has been argued that because developers are often required to purchase the Google-branded Android license, this has turned the theoretically open system into a freemium service.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Google licenses their Google Mobile Services software, along with the Android trademarks, only to hardware manufacturers for devices that meet Google's compatibility standards specified in the Android Compatibility Program document.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Thus, forks of Android that make major changes to the operating system itself do not include any of Google's non-free components, stay incompatible with applications that require them, and must ship with an alternative software marketplace in lieu of Google Play Store.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] A prominent example of such an Android fork is Amazon's Fire OS, which is used on the Kindle Fire line of tablets, and oriented toward Amazon services.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] The shipment of Android devices without GMS is also common in mainland China, as Google does not do business there.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In 2014, Google also began to require that all Android devices which license the Google Mobile Services software display a prominent "Powered by Android" logo on their boot screens.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In March 2018, it was reported that Google had begun to block "uncertified" Android devices from using Google Mobile Services software, and display a warning indicating that "the device manufacturer has preloaded Google apps and services without certification from Google".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Users of custom ROMs can register their device ID to their Google account to remove this block.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Moreover, open-source variants of some applications also exclude functions that are present in their non-free versions.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Apps that do not use Google components would also be at a functional disadvantage, as they can only use APIs contained within the OS itself.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In turn, third-party apps may have dependencies on Google Play Services.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Alibaba Group defended the allegations, arguing that the OS was a distinct platform from Android (primarily using HTML5 apps), but incorporated portions of Android's platform to allow backwards compatibility with third-party Android software.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Indeed, the devices did ship with an application store which offered Android apps; however, the majority of them were pirated.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Android received a lukewarm reaction when it was unveiled in 2007.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Although analysts were impressed with the respected technology companies that had partnered with Google to form the Open Handset Alliance, it was unclear whether mobile phone manufacturers would be willing to replace their existing operating systems with Android.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] The idea of an open-source, Linux-based development platform sparked interest, but there were additional worries about Android facing strong competition from established players in the smartphone market, such as Nokia and Microsoft, and rival Linux mobile operating systems that were in development.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Since then Android has grown to become the most widely used smartphone operating system and "one of the fastest mobile experiences available".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] As a result, it has been described by technology website *Ars Technica* as "practically the default operating system for launching new hardware" for companies without their own mobile platforms.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] This openness and flexibility is also present at the level of the end user: Android allows extensive customisation of devices by their owners and apps are freely available from non-Google app stores and third party websites.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] These have been cited as among the main advantages of Android phones over others.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Despite Android's popularity, including an activation rate three times that of iOS, there have been reports that Google has not been able to leverage their other products and web services successfully to turn Android into the money maker that analysts had expected.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In 2014, in an effort to improve prominence of the Android brand, Google began to require that devices featuring its proprietary components display an Android logo on the boot screen.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] For example, according to data from OpenSignal in July 2013, there were 11,868 models of Android devices, numerous screen sizes and eight Android OS versions simultaneously in use, while the large majority of iOS users have upgraded to the latest iteration of that OS.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Critics such as *Apple Insider* have asserted that fragmentation via hardware and software pushed Android's growth through large volumes of low end, budget-priced devices running older versions of Android.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] They maintain this forces Android developers to write for the "lowest common denominator" to reach as many users as possible, who have too little incentive to make use of the latest hardware or software features only available on a smaller percentage of devices.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] However, OpenSignal, who develops both Android and iOS apps, concluded that although fragmentation can make development trickier, Android's wider global reach also increases the potential reward.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Android is the largest mobile OS with 76% market share as of Q1 2025.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Android is the most used operating system on phones in many countries, with some countries, such as India, having over 96% market share.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] On tablets, usage is more even, as iOS is a bit more popular globally.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Research company Canalys estimated in the second quarter of 2009, that Android had a 2.8% share of worldwide smartphone shipments.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] By May 2010, Android had a 10% worldwide smartphone market share, overtaking Windows Mobile, whilst in the US Android held a 28% share, overtaking iPhone OS.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] By the fourth quarter of 2010, its worldwide share had grown to 33% of the market becoming the top-selling smartphone platform, overtaking Symbian.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In the US it became the top-selling platform in April 2011, overtaking BlackBerry OS with a 31.2% smartphone share, according to *comScore*.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] By the third quarter of 2011, Gartner estimated that more than half (52.5%) of the smartphone sales belonged to Android.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] By the third quarter of 2012 Android had a 75% share of the global smartphone market according to the research firm IDC.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In July 2011, Google said that 550,000 Android devices were being activated every day, up from 400,000 per day in May, and more than 100 million devices had been activated with 4.4% growth per week.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In September 2012, 500 million devices had been activated with 1.3 million activations per day.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In May 2013, at Google I/O, Sundar Pichai announced that 900 million Android devices had been activated.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Android market share varies by location.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In July 2012, "mobile subscribers aged 13+" in the United States using Android were up to 52%, and rose to 90% in China.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] During the third quarter of 2012, Android's worldwide smartphone shipment market share was 75%, with 750 million devices activated in total.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In April 2013, Android had 1.5 million activations per day.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] As of May 2013, 48 billion application ("app") installation have been performed from the Google Play store, and by September 2013, one billion Android devices had been activated.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] As of August 2020, the Google Play store had over 3 million Android applications published, and as of May 2016, apps had been downloaded more than 65 billion times.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] The operating system's success has made it a target for patent litigation as part of the so-called "smartphone wars" between technology companies.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Android devices account for more than half of smartphone sales in most markets, including the US, while "only in Japan was Apple on top" (September–November 2013 numbers).
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] At the end of 2013, over 1.5 billion Android smartphones had been sold in the four years since 2010, making Android the most sold phone and tablet OS.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Three billion Android smartphones were estimated to be sold by the end of 2014 (including previous years).
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] According to Gartner research company, Android-based devices outsold all contenders, every year since 2012.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In 2013, it outsold Windows 2.8:1 or by 573 million.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] As of 2015, Android has the largest installed base of all operating systems; Since 2013, devices running it also sell more than Windows, iOS and Mac OS X devices combined.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] According to StatCounter, which tracks only the use for browsing the web, Android is the most popular mobile operating system since August 2013.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Android is the most popular operating system for web browsing in India and several other countries (e.g. virtually all of Asia, with Japan and North Korea exceptions).
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Gartner expected the whole mobile phone market to "reach two billion units in 2016", including Android.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] According to a Statistica's estimate, Android smartphones had an installed base of 1.8 billion units in 2015, which was 76% of the estimated total number of smartphones worldwide.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Android has the largest installed base of any mobile operating system and, since 2013, the highest-selling operating system overall with sales in 2012, 2013 and 2014 close to the installed base of all PCs.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In the second quarter of 2014, Android's share of the global smartphone shipment market was 84.7%, a new record.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] This had grown to 87.5% worldwide market share by the third quarter of 2016, leaving main competitor iOS with 12.1% market share.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] According to an April 2017 StatCounter report, Android overtook Microsoft Windows to become the most popular operating system for total Internet usage.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] It has maintained the plurality since then.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In September 2015, Google announced that Android had 1.4 billion monthly active users.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] This changed to 2 billion monthly active users in May 2017.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Despite its success on smartphones, initially Android tablet adoption was slow, then later caught up with the iPad, in most countries.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] One of the main causes was the chicken or the egg situation where consumers were hesitant to buy an Android tablet due to a lack of high quality tablet applications, but developers were hesitant to spend time and resources developing tablet applications until there was a significant market for them.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] The content and app "ecosystem" proved more important than hardware specs as the selling point for tablets.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Due to the lack of Android tablet-specific applications in 2011, early Android tablets had to make do with existing smartphone applications that were ill-suited to larger screen sizes, whereas the dominance of Apple's iPad was reinforced by the large number of tablet-specific iOS applications.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Despite app support in its infancy, a considerable number of Android tablets, like the Barnes & Noble Nook (alongside those using other operating systems, such as the HP TouchPad and BlackBerry PlayBook) were rushed out to market in an attempt to capitalize on the success of the iPad.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] This approach, such as with the Dell Streak, failed to gain market traction with consumers as well as damaging the early reputation of Android tablets.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Furthermore, several Android tablets such as the Motorola Xoom were priced the same or higher than the iPad, which hurt sales.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] An exception was the Amazon Kindle Fire, which relied upon lower pricing as well as access to Amazon's ecosystem of applications and content.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] This began to change in 2012, with the release of the affordable Nexus 7 and a push by Google for developers to write better tablet applications.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] According to International Data Corporation, shipments of Android-powered tablets surpassed iPads in Q3 2012.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] As of the end of 2013, over 191.6 million Android tablets had sold in three years since 2011.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] This made Android tablets the most-sold type of tablet in 2013, surpassing iPads in the second quarter of 2013.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] According to StatCounter's web use statistics, as of 2020, Android tablets represent the majority of tablet devices used in Africa (70%), South America (65%), while less than half elsewhere, e.g.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] There are countries on all continents where Android tablets are the majority, for example, Mexico.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] India, and in Europe, with some notable exceptions such as the US (iPadOS 57%), and in China (iPadOS 53%)).
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Of all operating systems Android is first at 37%, followed by Windows at 28%, then iOS/iPadOS at 18%.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] The latest version Android 16 is the most popular Android version on smartphones and Android 14 on tablets.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] As of April 2026, the latest version Android 16 is most popular Android version on smartphones at 22%, followed by Android 15 (at 19%, down from 30% peak), 13, 14, 12 and 11.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Android is more used than iOS is virtually all countries, with few exceptions such as iOS has a 58% share in the US.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Android 16 is the most-used version in e.g.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] US, Europe, China, and Japan and Android 15 in India.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Usage of Android 13 and newer, i.e. supported versions, is at 69%, the rest of users are not supported with security updates; with recently supported Android 12 (last security updates in 2025), use is at 79%.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] On tablets, Android 14 is the most popular version overall (also in e.g.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] India, Russia, Canada, Australia, Europe and South America), at 19%.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Usage of Android 13 and newer, i.e. supported versions, is at 48.2% on Android tablets, and with Android 12, until recently supported, at 56.7%.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] The usage share varies a lot by country.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] 73% of US users use insecure Android tablets, and 78% of UK users, and the very old Android 9.0 Pie is still the most commonly used tablet version in both countries.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Paid Android applications in the past were simple to pirate.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In a May 2012 interview with *Eurogamer*, the developers of *Football Manager* stated that the ratio of pirated players vs legitimate players was 9:1 for their game *Football Manager Handheld*.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] However, not every developer agreed that piracy rates were an issue; for example, in July 2012 the developers of the game *Wind-up Knight* said that piracy levels of their game were only 12%, and most of the piracy came from China, where people cannot purchase apps from Google Play.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In 2010, Google released a tool for validating authorized purchases for use within apps, but developers complained that this was insufficient and trivial to crack.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Google responded that the tool, especially its initial release, was intended as a sample framework for developers to modify and build upon depending on their needs, not as a finished piracy solution.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Android "Jelly Bean" introduced the ability for paid applications to be encrypted, so that they may work only on the device for which they were purchased.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Android has been the subject of various cases of patent, copyright, and antitrust litigation.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] On August 12, 2010, Oracle sued Google over claimed infringement of copyrights and patents related to the Java programming language.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Oracle originally sought damages up to $6.1 billion, but this valuation was rejected by a United States federal judge who asked Oracle to revise the estimate.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In response, Google submitted multiple lines of defense, counterclaiming that Android did not infringe on Oracle's patents or copyright, that Oracle's patents were invalid, and several other defenses.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] They said that Android's Java runtime environment is based on Apache Harmony, a clean room implementation of the Java class libraries, and an independently developed virtual machine called Dalvik.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In May 2012, the jury in this case found that Google did not infringe on Oracle's patents, and the trial judge ruled that the structure of the Java APIs used by Google was not copyrightable.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] The parties agreed to zero dollars in statutory damages for a small amount of copied code.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] On May 9, 2014, the Federal Circuit partially reversed the district court ruling, ruling in Oracle's favor on the copyrightability issue, and remanding the issue of fair use to the district court.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In December 2015, Google announced that the next major release of Android (Android Nougat) would switch to OpenJDK, which is the official open-source implementation of the Java platform, instead of using the now-discontinued Apache Harmony project as its runtime.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Code reflecting this change was also posted to the AOSP source repository.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In its announcement, Google claimed this was part of an effort to create a "common code base" between Java on Android and other platforms.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In June 2016, a United States federal court ruled in favor of Google, stating that its use of the APIs was fair use.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In April 2021, the Supreme Court of the United States ruled that Google's use of the Java APIs was within the bounds of fair use, reversing the Federal Circuit Appeals Court ruling and remanding the case for further hearing.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] The majority opinion began with the assumption that the APIs may be copyrightable, and thus proceeded with a review of the factors that contributed to fair use.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In addition to lawsuits against Google directly, various proxy wars have been waged against Android indirectly by targeting manufacturers of Android devices, with the effect of discouraging manufacturers from adopting the platform by increasing the costs of bringing an Android device to market.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Both Apple and Microsoft have sued several manufacturers for patent infringement, with Apple's legal action against Samsung being a particularly high-profile case.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In January 2012, Microsoft said they had signed patent license agreements with eleven Android device manufacturers, whose products account for "70 percent of all Android smartphones" sold in the US and 55% of the worldwide revenue for Android devices.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Samsung's patent settlement with Microsoft included an agreement to allocate more resources to developing and marketing phones running Microsoft's Windows Phone operating system.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Microsoft has also tied its own Android software to patent licenses, requiring the bundling of Microsoft Office Mobile and Skype applications on Android devices to subsidize the licensing fees, while at the same time helping to promote its software lines.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Google has publicly expressed its frustration for the current patent landscape in the United States, accusing Apple, Oracle and Microsoft of trying to take down Android through patent litigation, rather than innovating and competing with better products and services.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In August 2011, Google purchased Motorola Mobility for US$12.5 billion, which was viewed in part as a defensive measure to protect Android, since Motorola Mobility held more than 17,000 patents.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In December 2011, Google bought over a thousand patents from IBM.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In 2013, FairSearch, a lobbying organization supported by Microsoft, Oracle and others, filed a complaint regarding Android with the European Commission, alleging that its free-of-charge distribution model constituted anti-competitive predatory pricing.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] The Free Software Foundation Europe, whose donors include Google, disputed the Fairsearch allegations.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In August 2016, Google was fined US$6.75 million by the Russian Federal Antimonopoly Service (FAS) under similar allegations by Yandex.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] The EU fined Google for €4.3 billion (about US$5 billion) and required the company to end this conduct within 90 days.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Google filed its appeal of the ruling in October 2018, though will not ask for any interim measures to delay the onset of conduct requirements.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] On October 16, 2018, Google announced that it would change its distribution model for Google Mobile Services in the EU, since part of its revenues streams for Android which came through use of Google Search and Chrome were now prohibited by the EU's ruling.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] While the core Android system remains free, OEMs in Europe would be required to purchase a paid license to the core suite of Google applications, such as Gmail, Google Maps and the Google Play Store.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Google Search will be licensed separately, with an option to include Google Chrome at no additional cost atop Search.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] European OEMs can bundle third-party alternatives on phones and devices sold to customers, if they so choose.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] OEMs will no longer be barred from selling any device running incompatible versions of Android in Europe.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Turkey's competition authority began investigating the default Android search engine in 2017, leading to a US$17.4 million fine in September 2018 and a fine of 0.05 percent of Google's revenue per day in November 2019 when Google did not meet the requirements.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In December 2019, Google stopped issuing licenses for new Android phone models sold in Turkey.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In September 2021, the Fair Trade Commission (South Korea) fined Google $177 million for restricting manufacturers, such as Samsung Electronics, from using modified versions of Android.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In 2025, the Competition Commission of India charged Google for "mandatory preinstallation of Google Play Store and other applications" on Android TV.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Google settled, unbundling the services and paying a $2.38 million fine.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Google has developed several variations of Android for specific use cases, including Android Wear, later renamed Wear OS, for wearable devices such as wrist watches, Android TV for televisions, Android Things for smart or Internet of things devices and Android Automotive for cars.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Additionally, by providing infrastructure that combines dedicated hardware and dedicated applications running on regular Android, Google have opened up the platform for its use in particular usage scenarios, such as the Android Auto app for cars, and Daydream, a Virtual Reality platform.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Additionally, Android has been installed and run on a variety of less-technical objects, including calculators, single-board computers, feature phones, electronic dictionaries, alarm clocks, refrigerators, landline telephones, coffee machines, bicycles, and mirrors.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Ouya, a video game console running Android, became one of the most successful Kickstarter campaigns, crowdfunding US$8.5m for its development, and was later followed by other Android-based consoles, such as Nvidia's Shield Portable – an Android device in a video game controller form factor.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In 2011, Google demonstrated "Android@Home", a home automation technology which uses Android to control a range of household devices including light switches, power sockets and thermostats.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Prototype light bulbs were announced that could be controlled from an Android phone or tablet, but Android head Andy Rubin was cautious to note that "turning a lightbulb on and off is nothing new", pointing to numerous failed home automation services.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Google, he said, was thinking more ambitiously and the intention was to use their position as a cloud services provider to bring Google products into customers' homes.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Parrot unveiled an Android-based car stereo system known as Asteroid in 2011, followed by a successor, the touchscreen-based Asteroid Smart, in 2012.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In 2013, Clarion released its own Android-based car stereo, the AX1.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Android comes preinstalled on a few laptops (a similar functionality of running Android applications is also available in Google's ChromeOS) and can also be installed on personal computers by end users.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] On those platforms Android provides additional functionality for physical keyboards and mice, together with the "Alt-Tab" key combination for switching applications quickly with a keyboard.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In December 2014, one reviewer commented that Android's notification system is "vastly more complete and robust than in most environments" and that Android is "absolutely usable" as one's primary desktop operating system.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In October 2015, *The Wall Street Journal* reported that Android will serve as Google's future main laptop operating system, with the plan to fold ChromeOS into it by 2017.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] That is unlike Android where support is shorter with "EOL dates [being..] at least 3 years [into the future] for Android tablets for education".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] At Google I/O in May 2016, Google announced Daydream, a virtual reality platform that relied on a smartphone and provided VR capabilities through a virtual reality headset and controller designed by Google itself.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] However, this did not catch on and was discontinued in 2019.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] The mascot of Android is a green android robot, as related to the software's name.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Although it had no official name for a long time, the Android team at Google reportedly call it "Bugdroid".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] In 2024, a Google blog post revealed its official name, "The Bot".
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] It was designed by then-Google graphic designer Irina Blok on November 5, 2007, when Android was announced.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Contrary to reports that she was tasked with a project to create an icon, Blok confirmed in an interview that she independently developed it and made it open source.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] The robot design was initially not presented to Google, but it quickly became commonplace in the Android development team, with various variations of it created by the developers there who liked the figure, as it was free under a Creative Commons license.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-operating-system-p03] Its popularity amongst the development team eventually led to Google adopting it as an official icon as part of the Android logo when it launched to consumers in 2008.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] Android 2.2 "Froyo" brought trace-based just-in-time (JIT) compilation into Dalvik, optimizing the execution of applications by continually profiling applications each time they run and dynamically compiling frequently executed short segments of their bytecode into native machine code.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] While Dalvik interprets the rest of an application's bytecode, native execution of those short bytecode segments, called "traces", provides significant performance improvements.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] Unlike Dalvik, ART introduces the use of ahead-of-time (AOT) compilation by compiling the most performance-critical parts of applications (previously, the entire app) into native machine code upon their installation.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] This way, ART improves the overall execution efficiency and reduces power consumption, which results in improved battery autonomy on mobile devices.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] At the same time, ART brings faster execution of applications, improved memory allocation and garbage collection (GC) mechanisms, new applications debugging features, and more accurate high-level profiling of applications.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] To maintain backward compatibility, ART uses the same input bytecode as Dalvik, supplied through standard .dex files as part of APK files, while the .odex files are replaced with Executable and Linkable Format (ELF) executables.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] Once an application is compiled by using ART's on-device dex2oat utility, it is run from the compiled ELF executable; as a result, ART eliminates various application execution overheads associated with Dalvik's interpretation and trace-based JIT compilation.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] Initially, a disadvantage of ART was that additional time was required for compilation when an application was installed, and applications took up slightly more secondary storage (usually flash memory) to store the compiled code.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] Long AOT compilation became especially problematic when monthly security updates became the norm, locking users out of the OS for a long time after each update.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] To improve on this, a hybrid approach was introduced in Android 7.0 (Nougat).
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] Newly installed apps run using JIT compilation, and get profiled by the runtime.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] When the device is idle and charging, the runtime performs AOT compilation on the most frequently used ("hot") code.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] Android 4.4 "KitKat" introduced a technology preview of ART as an alternative runtime environment to Dalvik, which remained the default virtual machine.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] In the subsequent major Android release, Android 5.0 "Lollipop", Dalvik was entirely replaced by ART.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] Android 7.0 "Nougat" turned the ART from a pure AOT to a hybrid JIT/AOT solution, while switching its Java Runtime Environment from the discontinued Apache Harmony to OpenJDK, introducing a JIT compiler with code profiling.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] Less-frequently used code relies on JIT compilation.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] Android 9 "Pie" reduced the amount of storage used by APKs by using compressed bytecode files, and profiler data can be uploaded to Google Play servers to be bundled with apps when downloaded by users with a similar device, which shortens download time from Google Play by up to 40%.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] Google Play cloud profiles allow apps to be optimized on installation, which helps avoid the initial performance issues present on Android 7.0 to 8.1.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] In July 2021, the concept of baseline profiles was introduced.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] Baseline profiles are ART profiles that define methods and classes which should undergo AOT compilation from an app's first launch, and are compatible with Android 7.0 and later.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] They provide similar functionality to Android 9's Google Play cloud profiles when they are not available and automatically merge with cloud profiles when they are available.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] Baseline profiles are included with releases of AndroidX libraries and Jetpack Compose.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] ART was updated with a new garbage collector (GC) utilizing the Linux userfaultfd system call in Android 13.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] It reduces memory pressure, compiled code size and jank, and prevents the risk of killing apps because of low memory during garbage collection.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] Other changes also improve app startup, reduce jank and improve performance.
[src:android-runtime-art/android-runtime] Because of the Mainline project, Android 12's ART will also be updated.
[src:android-runtime-art/bytecode] The name *bytecode* stems from instruction sets that have one-byte opcodes followed by optional parameters.
[src:android-runtime-art/bytecode] Intermediate representations such as bytecode may be output by programming language implementations to ease interpretation, or it may be used to reduce hardware and operating system dependence by allowing the same code to run cross-platform, on different devices.
[src:android-runtime-art/bytecode] Bytecode may often be either directly executed on a virtual machine (a p-code machine, i.e., interpreter), or it may be further compiled into machine code for better performance.
[src:android-runtime-art/bytecode] Since bytecode instructions are processed by software, they may be arbitrarily complex, but are nonetheless often akin to traditional hardware instructions: virtual stack machines are the most common, but virtual register machines have been built also.
[src:android-runtime-art/bytecode] Different parts may often be stored in separate files, similar to object modules, but dynamically loaded during execution.
[src:android-runtime-art/bytecode] A bytecode program may be executed by parsing and *directly* executing the instructions, one at a time.
[src:android-runtime-art/bytecode] This kind of *bytecode interpreter* is very portable.
[src:android-runtime-art/bytecode] Some systems, called dynamic translators, or *just-in-time* (JIT) compilers, translate bytecode into machine code as necessary at runtime.
[src:android-runtime-art/bytecode] This makes the virtual machine hardware-specific but does not lose the portability of the bytecode.
[src:android-runtime-art/bytecode] For example, Java and Smalltalk code is typically stored in bytecode format, which is typically then JIT compiled to translate the bytecode to machine code before execution.
[src:android-runtime-art/bytecode] This introduces a delay before a program is run, when the bytecode is compiled to native machine code, but improves execution speed considerably compared to interpreting source code directly, normally by around an order of magnitude (10x).
[src:android-runtime-art/bytecode] Because of its performance advantage, today many language implementations execute a program in two phases, first compiling the source code into bytecode, and then passing the bytecode to the virtual machine.
[src:android-runtime-art/bytecode] There are bytecode based virtual machines of this sort for Java, Raku, Python, PHP, Tcl, mawk and Forth (however, Forth is seldom compiled via bytecodes in this way, and its virtual machine is more generic instead).
[src:android-runtime-art/bytecode] The implementation of Perl and Ruby 1.8 instead work by walking an abstract syntax tree representation derived from the source code.
[src:android-runtime-art/bytecode] More recently, the authors of V8 and Dart have challenged the notion that intermediate bytecode is needed for fast and efficient VM implementation.
[src:android-runtime-art/bytecode] Both of these language implementations currently do direct JIT compiling from source code to machine code with no bytecode intermediary.
[src:android-runtime-art/bytecode] Compiled code can be analysed and investigated using a built-in tool for debugging the low-level bytecode.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] The compact Dalvik Executable format is designed for systems that are constrained in terms of memory and processor speed.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] The successor of Dalvik is Android Runtime (ART), which uses the same bytecode and .dex files (but not .odex files), with the succession aiming at performance improvements.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] The new runtime environment was included for the first time in Android 4.4 "KitKat" as a technology preview, and replaced Dalvik entirely in later versions; Android 5.0 "Lollipop" is the first version in which ART is the only included runtime.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] Android Native Development Kit which eventually paved way for C++ support has existed since Dalvik's first public release.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] According to Bornstein, Memory-mapping executables and libraries across multiple process and building a faster interpreter with register-based semantics drove much of the early design of the byte-aligned instruction set and the Virtual Machine.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] Experience working with J2ME on Sidekick at Danger, Bornstein found it was too stripped down and fairly constrained for Android.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] While improvements such as Isolates as then planned by Sun made process isolation infeasible as it broke Android's intra-Device security model.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] For Dalvik VM, Bornstein particularly took inspiration from *The Case for Register Machines* authored by Brian Davis et al. of Trinity College, Dublin.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] Dalvik was open sourced under Apache License v2 as rest of the Android Open Source Project in 2008.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] Unlike Java Virtual Machines, which are stack machines, the Dalvik VM uses a register-based architecture that requires fewer, typically more complex, virtual machine instructions.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] Dalvik programs are written in Java using the Android application programming interface (API), compiled to Java bytecode, and converted to Dalvik instructions as necessary.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] A tool called `dx` is used to convert Java .class files into the .dex format.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] Multiple classes are included in a single .dex file.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] Duplicate strings and other constants used in multiple class files are included only once in the .dex output to conserve space.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] Java bytecode is also converted into an alternative instruction set used by the Dalvik VM.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] An uncompressed .dex file is typically a few percent smaller in size than a compressed Java archive (JAR) derived from the same .class files.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] The Dalvik executables may be modified again when installed onto a mobile device.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] In order to gain further optimizations, byte order may be swapped in certain data, simple data structures and function libraries may be linked inline, and empty class objects may be short-circuited, for example.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] The design of Dalvik permits a device to run multiple instances of the VM efficiently.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] While Dalvik interprets the rest of application's bytecode, native execution of those short bytecode segments, called "traces", provides significant performance improvements.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] The potential trace heads are identified in the front-end of the compiler at the parsing stage and after the bytecode conversion.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] A translation cache is maintained during the runtime.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] Multiple traces can be chained to reduce synchronisation between the compiler and the interpreter.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] The trace is optimized by converting it into the Single Static Assignment form, enabling optimizations like dead store elimination, variable folding, and inlining getters and setters.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] The relative merits of stack machines versus register-based approaches are a subject of ongoing debate.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] This difference is of importance to VM interpreters, for which opcode dispatch tends to be expensive, along with other factors similarly relevant to just-in-time compilation.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] Tests performed on ARMv7 devices in 2010 by Oracle (owner of the Java technology) with standard non-graphical Java benchmarks showed the HotSpot VM of Java SE embedded to be 2–3 times faster than the JIT-based Dalvik VM of Android 2.2 (the initial Android release that included a JIT compiler).
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] In 2012, academic benchmarks confirmed the factor of 3 between HotSpot and Dalvik on the same Android board, also noting that Dalvik code was not smaller than Hotspot.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] Furthermore, as of March 2014, benchmarks performed on an Android device still show up to a factor 100 between native applications and a Dalvik application on the same Android device.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] Upon running benchmarks using the early interpreter of 2009, both Java Native Interface (JNI) and native code showed an order of magnitude speedup.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] Dalvik is published under the terms of the Apache License 2.0.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] Some say that Dalvik is a clean-room implementation rather than a development on top of a standard Java runtime, which would mean it does not inherit copyright-based license restrictions from either the standard-edition or open-source-edition Java runtimes.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] On August 12, 2010, Oracle, which acquired Sun Microsystems in April 2009 and therefore owns the rights to Java, sued Google over claimed infringement of copyrights and patents.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] Oracle alleged that Google, in developing Android, knowingly, directly and repeatedly infringed Oracle's Java-related intellectual property.
[src:android-runtime-art/dalvik-software] The parties agreed to zero dollars in statutory damages for 9 lines of copied code.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] A **Java virtual machine** (**JVM**) is a virtual machine that enables a computer to run Java programs as well as programs written in other languages, other languages referred to as JVM languages that are also compiled to Java bytecode.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The JVM is detailed by a specification that formally describes what is required in a JVM implementation.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Having a specification ensures interoperability of Java programs across different implementations so that program authors using the Java Development Kit (JDK) need not worry about idiosyncrasies of the underlying hardware platform.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The JVM reference implementation is developed by the OpenJDK project as open source code and includes a JIT compiler called HotSpot.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The commercially supported Java releases available from Oracle are based on the OpenJDK runtime.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Eclipse OpenJ9 is another open source JVM for OpenJDK.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The Java virtual machine is an abstract (virtual) computer defined by a specification.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] It is a part of the Java Runtime Environment.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The garbage collection algorithm used and any internal optimization of the Java virtual machine instructions (their translation into machine code) are not specified.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The main reason for this omission is to not unnecessarily constrain implementers.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Any Java application can be run only inside some concrete implementation of the abstract specification of the Java virtual machine.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Starting with Java Platform, Standard Edition (J2SE) 5.0, changes to the JVM specification have been developed under the Java Community Process as JSR 924.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] As of 2006, changes to the specification to support changes proposed to the class file format (JSR 202) are being done as a maintenance release of JSR 924.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The most commonly used Java virtual machine is Oracle's HotSpot.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Oracle owns the Java trademark and may allow its use to certify implementation suites as fully compatible with Oracle's specification.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Java's design philosophy revolves around the assumption of a garbage collector.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Unlike languages such as C++ and Rust, deterministic memory management through a `delete` keyword (as in C++) is not possible.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Even introducing such a feature is not possible, due to a lack of ownership, aside from using sun.misc.Unsafe or through java.lang.foreign to allocate/deallocate memory outside the Java heap.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Due to Java primarily using heap-based allocation, objects are stored as references, and deletion would result in dangling pointers.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The JVM operates on specific types of data as specified in Java Virtual Machine specifications.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The data types can be divided into primitive types (integer and floating-point values) and reference types.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] `long` and `double` types, which are 64-bits, are supported natively, but consume two units of storage in a frame's local variables or operand stack, since each unit is 32 bits.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] `boolean`, `byte`, `short`, and `char` types are all sign-extended (except `char` which is zero-extended) and operated on as 32-bit integers, the same as `int` types.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The smaller types only have a few type-specific instructions for loading, storing, and type conversion.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] `boolean` is operated on as 8-bit `byte` values, with 0 representing `false` and 1 representing `true`.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] (Although `boolean` has been treated as a type since *The Java Virtual Machine Specification, Second Edition* clarified this issue, in compiled and executed code there is little difference between a `boolean` and a `byte` except for name mangling in method signatures and the type of Boolean arrays.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] `boolean`s in method signatures are mangled as `Z` while `byte`s are mangled as `B`.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Boolean arrays carry the type `boolean[]` but use 8 bits per element, and the JVM has no built-in capability to pack booleans into a bit array, so except for the type they perform and behave the same as `byte` arrays.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The JVM has a garbage-collected heap for storing objects and arrays.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Code, constants, and other class data are stored in the "method area".
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The method area is logically part of the heap, but implementations may treat the method area separately from the heap, and for example might not garbage collect it.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Each JVM thread also has its own call stack (called a "Java Virtual Machine stack" for clarity), which stores frames.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] A new frame is created each time a method is called, and the frame is destroyed when that method exits.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Each frame provides an "operand stack" and an array of "local variables".
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The operand stack is used for operands to run computations and for receiving the return value of a called method, while local variables serve the same purpose as registers and are also used to pass method arguments.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Thus, the JVM is both a stack machine and a register machine.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] In practice, HotSpot eliminates every stack besides the native thread/call stack even when running in Interpreted mode, as its Templating Interpreter technically functions as a compiler.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The JVM uses references and stack/array indexes to address data; it does not use byte addressing like most physical machines do, so it does not neatly fit the usual categorization of 32-bit or 64-bit machines.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] In one sense, it could be classified as a 32-bit machine, since this is the size of the largest value it natively stores: a 32-bit integer or floating-point value or a 32-bit reference.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Because a reference is 32 bits, each program is limited to at most 232 unique references and therefore at most 232 objects.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] However, each object can be more than one byte large, and potentially *very* large; the largest possible object is an array of `long` of length 231 - 1 which would consume 16 GiB of memory, and there could potentially be 232 of these if there were enough memory available.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] This results in upper bounds that are more comparable to a typical 64-bit byte-addressable machine.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] A JVM implementation can be designed to run on a processor that natively uses any bit width as long as it correctly implements the integer (8-, 16-, 32-, and 64-bit) and floating-point (32- and 64-bit) math that the JVM requires.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Depending on the method used to implement references (native pointers, compressed pointers, or an indirection table), this can limit the number of objects to less than the theoretical maximum.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] A JVM language is any language with functions that can be expressed in a valid class file, which can be hosted by a JVM.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] A class file contains JVM instructions (JVM bytecode), a symbol table, and other ancillary information.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The class file format is the hardware- and operating system-independent binary format used to represent compiled classes and interfaces.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] There are several JVM languages, both older established languages ported to JVM, and much newer from-scratch languages.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] JRuby and Jython may be the best known ports of older languages, i.e., Ruby and Python respectively.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Of the new from-scratch languages created to compile to Java bytecode, Clojure, Groovy, Scala and Kotlin may be the most popular.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] A notable feature of the JVM languages is their language interoperability, they are compatible with each other, so that, for example, Scala libraries can be used with Java programs and vice versa.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Java 7 JVM implements *JSR 292: Supporting Dynamically Typed Languages* on the Java Platform, a new feature which supports dynamically typed languages in the JVM.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] This feature is developed within the Da Vinci Machine project whose mission is to extend the JVM so that it supports languages other than Java.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] One of the organizational units of JVM byte code is a class.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] A class loader implementation must be able to recognize and load anything that conforms to the Java class file format.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Any implementation is free to recognize other binary forms besides *class* files, but it must recognize *class* files.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Initialization: invokes Java code that initializes class variables to their proper starting values.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] In general, there are three types of class loader: bootstrap class loader, extension class loader and System / Application class loader.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Every Java virtual machine implementation must have a bootstrap class loader that is capable of loading trusted classes, as well as an extension class loader or application class loader.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The Java virtual machine specification does not specify how a class loader should locate classes.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Each particular host operating system needs its own implementation of the JVM and runtime.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] These JVMs interpret the bytecode semantically the same way, but the actual implementation may be different.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] More complex than just emulating bytecode is compatibly and efficiently implementing the Java core API that must be mapped to each host operating system.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] These instructions operate on a set of common abstracted data types rather the native data types of any specific instruction set architecture.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Furthermore, common programmer errors that often led to data corruption or unpredictable behavior such as accessing off the end of an array or using an uninitialized pointer are not allowed to occur.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Several features of Java combine to provide this safety, including the class model, the garbage-collected heap, and the verifier.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The JVM verifies all bytecode before it is executed.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The first two of these checks take place primarily during the verification step that occurs when a class is loaded and made eligible for use.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The third is primarily performed dynamically, when data items or methods of a class are first accessed by another class.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The verifier permits only some bytecode sequences in valid programs, e.g. a jump (branch) instruction can only target an instruction within the same method.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Furthermore, the verifier ensures that any given instruction operates on a fixed stack location, allowing the JIT compiler to transform stack accesses into fixed register accesses.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Because of this, that the JVM is a stack architecture does not imply a speed penalty for emulation on register-based architectures when using a JIT compiler.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] In the face of the code-verified JVM architecture, it makes no difference to a JIT compiler whether it gets named imaginary registers or imaginary stack positions that must be allocated to the target architecture's registers.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] In fact, code verification makes the JVM different from a classic stack architecture, of which efficient emulation with a JIT compiler is more complicated and typically carried out by a slower interpreter.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Additionally, the Interpreter used by the default JVM is a special type known as a Template Interpreter, which translates bytecode directly to native, register based machine language rather than emulate a stack like a typical interpreter.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Another instance of a stack architecture being merely a specification and implemented in a register based virtual machine is the Common Language Runtime.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The original specification for the bytecode verifier used natural language that was incomplete or incorrect in some respects.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] A number of attempts have been made to specify the JVM as a formal system.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] By doing this, the security of current JVM implementations can more thoroughly be analyzed, and potential security exploits prevented.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] It will also be possible to optimize the JVM by skipping unnecessary safety checks, if the application being run is proven to be safe.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] A virtual machine architecture allows very fine-grained control over the actions that code within the machine is permitted to take.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] It assumes the code is "semantically" correct, that is, it successfully passed the (formal) bytecode verifier process, materialized by a tool, possibly off-board the virtual machine.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] This is designed to allow safe execution of untrusted code from remote sources, a model used by Java applets, and other secure code downloads.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Once bytecode-verified, the downloaded code runs in a restricted "sandbox", which is designed to protect the user from misbehaving or malicious code.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] As an addition to the bytecode verification process, publishers can purchase a certificate with which to digitally sign applets as safe, giving them permission to ask the user to break out of the sandbox and access the local file system, clipboard, execute external pieces of software, or network.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] For each hardware architecture a different Java bytecode interpreter is needed.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] When a computer has a Java bytecode interpreter, it can run any Java bytecode program, and the same program can be run on any computer that has such an interpreter.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] When Java bytecode is executed by an interpreter, the execution will always be slower than the execution of the same program compiled into native machine language.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] This problem is mitigated by just-in-time (JIT) compilers for executing Java bytecode.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] A JIT compiler may translate Java bytecode into native machine language while executing the program.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The translated parts of the program can then be executed much more quickly than they could be interpreted.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] This technique gets applied to those parts of a program frequently executed.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] This way a JIT compiler can significantly speed up the overall execution time.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] There is no necessary connection between the Java programming language and Java bytecode.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] A program written in Java can be compiled directly into the machine language of a real computer and programs written in other languages than Java can be compiled into Java bytecode.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Java bytecode is intended to be platform-independent and secure.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Some JVM implementations do not include an interpreter, but consist only of a just-in-time compiler.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Java 22 introduces the Foreign Function and Memory API, which can be seen as the successor to Java Native Interface.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Native methods are enable by JNI to handle situations when an application cannot be written entirely in the Java programming language, e.g. when the standard Java class library does not support the platform-specific features or program library.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The JNI framework lets a native method use Java objects in the same way that Java code uses these objects.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] A native method can create Java objects and then inspect and use these objects to perform its tasks.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] A native method can also inspect and use objects created by Java application code.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] JNI also allows direct access to assembly code, without even going through a C bridge.[3] Accessing Java applications from assembly is possible in the same way.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] At the start of the Java platform's lifetime, the JVM was marketed as a web technology for creating Rich Web Applications.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] As of 2018, most web browsers and operating systems bundling web browsers do not ship with a Java plug-in, nor do they permit side-loading any non-Flash plug-in.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The Java browser plugin was deprecated in JDK 9.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The NPAPI Java browser plug-in was designed to allow the JVM to execute so-called Java applets embedded into HTML pages.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] For browsers with the plug-in installed, the applet is allowed to draw into a rectangular region on the page assigned to it.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Because the plug-in includes a JVM, Java applets are not restricted to the Java programming language; any language targeting the JVM may run in the plug-in.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] A restricted set of APIs allow applets access to the user's microphone or 3D acceleration, although applets are not able to modify the page outside its rectangular region.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Adobe Flash Player, the main competing technology, works in the same way in this respect.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] As of June 2015 according to W3Techs, Java applet and Silverlight use had fallen to 0.1% each for all web sites, while Flash had fallen to 10.8%.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Since May 2016, JavaPoly allows users to import unmodified Java libraries, and invoke them directly from JavaScript.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] JavaPoly allows websites to use unmodified Java libraries, even if the user does not have Java installed on their computer.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] With the continuing improvements in JavaScript execution speed, combined with the increased use of mobile devices whose web browsers do not implement support for plugins, there are efforts to target those users through transpilation to JavaScript.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] It is possible to either transpile the source code or JVM bytecode to JavaScript.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Compiling the JVM bytecode, which is universal across JVM languages, allows building upon the language's existing compiler to bytecode.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] The main JVM bytecode to JavaScript transpilers are TeaVM, the compiler contained in Dragome Web SDK, Bck2Brwsr, and j2js-compiler.
[src:android-runtime-art/java-virtual-machine] Leading transpilers from JVM languages to JavaScript include the Java-to-JavaScript transpiler contained in Google Web Toolkit, J2CL, Clojurescript (Clojure), GrooScript (Apache Groovy), Scala.js (Scala) and others.
